 change within the communities in which they operated.The Young Lords offers readers the opportunity to learn about this vibrant organization through their own words and images, collecting an array of their essays, journalism, photographs, speeches, and pamphlets. Organized topically and thematically, this volume highlights the Young Lords’ diverse and inventive activism around issues such as education, health care, gentrification, police injustice and gender equality, as well as self-determination for Puerto Rico.In recovering these rare written and visual materials, Darrel Enck-Wanzer has given voice to the lost chorus of the Young Lords, while providing an indispensable resource for students, scholars, activists, and others interested in learning about this influential grassroots “street political” organization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil rights and socialismzUnited StatesxHistoryvSources. 0aPolitical activistszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aPuerto RicansxEthnic identityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPuerto RicansxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryvSources. 0aPuerto RicanszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aPuerto RicanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxPolitics and governmenty20th centuryvSources. 0aPuerto RicanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditionsy20th centuryvSources. 0aReaders. 0aSocial justicezUnited StatesxHistoryvSources. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aEnck-Wanzer, Darrel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnck-Wanzer, Darrel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorales, Iris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver-Velez, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part o